SIMPLE: fiduciary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fiduciary
<hw>Fi*du"ci*a*ry</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>fiduciarus</ets>, fr. <ets>fiducia</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>fiduciaire</ets>. See <er>Fiducial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Involving confidence or trust; confident; undoubting; faithful;
firm; <as>as, in a <ex>fiduciary</ex> capacity</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Fiduciary</xex> obedience.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Howell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Holding, held, or founded, in trust.</def>
<rj><au>Spelman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fiduciary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fiduciary
<hw>Fi*du"ci*a*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who holds a
thing in trust for another; a trustee.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Instrumental to the conveying God's blessing upon those whose
<qex>fiduciaries</qex> they are.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>One who depends for salvation on
faith, without works; an Antinomian.</def>
<rj><au>Hammond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fie</ent>⟦br⟧
